1
00:00:05,349 --> 00:00:08,650
We are here today to talk about Always Be Composing,

2
00:00:08,791 --> 00:00:12,092
the flexible music system of Plants vs. Zombies Heroes.

3
00:00:14,293 --> 00:00:17,134
I am Becky Allen, audio director and composer

4
00:00:17,174 --> 00:00:21,596
at PopCap Games, and I worked on Plants vs. Zombies Heroes

5
00:00:21,616 --> 00:00:22,776
for the last two years.

6
00:00:23,697 --> 00:00:26,158
You may say, what is Plants vs. Zombies Heroes?

7
00:00:27,718 --> 00:00:30,019
A collectible card game, that's right.

8
00:00:30,299 --> 00:00:32,280
Who here has heard of it, played it?

9
00:00:32,820 --> 00:00:34,441
Yay, all right, thanks.

10
00:00:36,143 --> 00:00:41,364
So, this is an interesting project, so I'm here to talk about the music design, the music

11
00:00:41,404 --> 00:00:46,826
systems and the composition, and all of the different phases of iteration throughout the

12
00:00:46,866 --> 00:00:47,346
process.

13
00:00:49,686 --> 00:00:50,727
We'll start at the beginning.

14
00:00:53,027 --> 00:00:58,628
At the very beginning, I decided on a guiding principle, support gameplay and the player's

15
00:00:58,728 --> 00:00:59,309
experience.

16
00:01:00,249 --> 00:01:04,150
I met with the game designer, Devon Lowe, and talked about...

17
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:05,620
the music for the game.

18
00:01:06,581 --> 00:01:09,162
We'd already made a prototype of the game in Unity

19
00:01:09,642 --> 00:01:12,263
and with Wwise and put in some initial hooks,

20
00:01:12,603 --> 00:01:15,804
lots of hooks actually, utilizing old PVZ sounds.

21
00:01:17,285 --> 00:01:19,246
But we knew that this was going to be a new game

22
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:22,467
in a new genre with CCG,

23
00:01:23,448 --> 00:01:26,429
but still in the PVZ franchise, PVZ universe.

24
00:01:27,769 --> 00:01:30,631
Also at that time, Hearthstone was very popular

25
00:01:30,731 --> 00:01:33,472
and still is very popular, awesome game.

26
00:01:34,647 --> 00:01:35,528
and awesome sounding game.

27
00:01:36,449 --> 00:01:39,712
So we were looking at that and seeing how that sounded

28
00:01:39,872 --> 00:01:41,814
and music and sound design and that,

29
00:01:42,675 --> 00:01:45,757
and also looking back to other PVZ games,

30
00:01:46,278 --> 00:01:47,279
and I was thinking, hmm,

31
00:01:47,899 --> 00:01:49,421
how can I stretch out a little more here?

32
00:01:49,961 --> 00:01:52,083
I wanna support the gameplay and the player's experience

33
00:01:52,123 --> 00:01:55,266
maybe even more with more interactivity,

34
00:01:55,686 --> 00:01:56,787
a little more responsiveness,

35
00:01:58,068 --> 00:02:00,971
move that needle a little further for this project.

36
00:02:02,567 --> 00:02:06,191
And meeting with the game designer, we talked initially about what was he

37
00:02:06,231 --> 00:02:07,292
envisioning for the music.

38
00:02:07,872 --> 00:02:11,816
And he said, well, I'd like there to be a progression, like a beginning,

39
00:02:11,836 --> 00:02:15,980
a middle, and yeah, some kind of development there, so

40
00:02:16,020 --> 00:02:17,621
that you feel the progression of the game.

41
00:02:18,362 --> 00:02:22,866
And also there would be heroes in this game, so whatever that would mean.

42
00:02:25,979 --> 00:02:33,041
So this is the early phase and thinking about different music styles and influences,

43
00:02:34,422 --> 00:02:37,863
there was a lot of pressure early on from the team to make this sound very

44
00:02:37,963 --> 00:02:46,425
PVZ1-ish, and even a little PVZ2, because they wanted the players to come over

45
00:02:46,485 --> 00:02:48,526
from other PVZ games into PVZ.

46
00:02:50,304 --> 00:02:54,648
So I did listen to a lot of PVZ themes,

47
00:02:54,708 --> 00:02:57,069
especially PVZ1 themes by Laura Shigehara.

48
00:02:57,730 --> 00:03:01,853
Of course, the wonderful PVZ2 themes of Peter McConnell are fantastic as well.

49
00:03:03,054 --> 00:03:06,997
But I did sit down with Laura's music and analyze that.

50
00:03:07,357 --> 00:03:12,181
And so I sat in my studio and just kind of analyzed that in a traditional, analytical way.

51
00:03:13,061 --> 00:03:16,424
And I was like, okay, mostly minor, lots of bass lines.

52
00:03:16,868 --> 00:03:19,290
incredible melodies, strong melodies.

53
00:03:20,110 --> 00:03:22,612
So I sat in my studio and I started writing

54
00:03:22,652 --> 00:03:24,053
and trying to write in that style

55
00:03:24,893 --> 00:03:26,835
and finding what are the edges of that style.

56
00:03:27,095 --> 00:03:29,477
Oh, if I do this too much, it doesn't feel PVC.

57
00:03:29,877 --> 00:03:33,119
If I go over there too much, it doesn't feel too PVC

58
00:03:33,159 --> 00:03:36,802
and finding where those edges are and still feeling PVC.

59
00:03:37,762 --> 00:03:38,803
So I was doing that for a little while.

60
00:03:39,704 --> 00:03:42,425
Meanwhile, during this sort of explorational style phase,

61
00:03:42,946 --> 00:03:45,908
I was doing a lot of yoga in the morning at home.

62
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:48,643
And my daughter was watching Power Puffs in the background,

63
00:03:49,243 --> 00:03:51,786
and I would hear the music of the Power Puffs,

64
00:03:51,846 --> 00:03:54,168
and I'd hear these little fragments,

65
00:03:54,208 --> 00:03:57,351
these little personal stingers and small phrases

66
00:03:57,391 --> 00:03:59,654
that were kind of in and out and really fast,

67
00:03:59,694 --> 00:04:02,336
but very identifiable, and I really liked that.

68
00:04:02,697 --> 00:04:04,979
And I thought, hmm, maybe that also

69
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:07,481
could influence PVC Heroes.

70
00:04:10,818 --> 00:04:18,022
So we had a gameplay prototype and in order to really flesh out some of these ideas,

71
00:04:18,602 --> 00:04:22,264
I took a linear capture of that gameplay prototype and brought it into my DAW

72
00:04:23,305 --> 00:04:29,128
and started exploring with some themes and thinking about what the role of the music would be.

73
00:04:29,148 --> 00:04:34,431
I talked to Devin Lowe again, our creative director, and asked him,

74
00:04:35,492 --> 00:04:38,473
What are the average number of hands, do you think, in this game?

75
00:04:39,343 --> 00:04:41,444
Well, I think probably about eight hands would do.

76
00:04:42,385 --> 00:04:45,606
And how long do you think an average session length would be?

77
00:04:45,866 --> 00:04:47,106
He said about five minutes.

78
00:04:48,027 --> 00:04:48,307
Okay.

79
00:04:49,007 --> 00:04:51,848
And then he said, there's also going to be these sections

80
00:04:51,908 --> 00:04:54,169
in the game where you play actively,

81
00:04:54,489 --> 00:04:56,250
and then a fight combat section

82
00:04:56,330 --> 00:04:57,931
where the game sort of plays for you

83
00:04:57,991 --> 00:05:00,132
and the cards are battling against each other.

84
00:05:00,152 --> 00:05:01,292
I'm like, okay.

85
00:05:01,912 --> 00:05:02,853
Getting the ideas here.

86
00:05:03,533 --> 00:05:05,274
And he also said there will be 20 heroes.

87
00:05:06,808 --> 00:05:09,529
10 plant heroes and 10 zombie heroes.

88
00:05:11,110 --> 00:05:18,473
So I started to explore and this is an early prototype of the music where I'm exploring

89
00:05:19,433 --> 00:05:25,635
the hero themes. So this guy down here, Super Brains on the bottom, he's our zombie hero,

90
00:05:25,655 --> 00:05:30,938
and up at the top is Green Shadow, our plant hero. And you'll hear three different things in here.

91
00:05:31,598 --> 00:05:36,160
The zombie theme for Super Brains and then the plant theme.

92
00:05:36,714 --> 00:05:41,374
for Green Shadow and the combat fight section, so three different things playing.

93
00:06:06,327 --> 00:06:12,372
Back to super brains. ♪

94
00:06:12,512 --> 00:06:15,094
Bright shadows coming in. ♪

95
00:06:36,907 --> 00:06:42,051
So during this proof of concept phase, I was trying to explore going back and forth between

96
00:06:42,071 --> 00:06:48,757
the heroes and also that combat music because really at that stage they didn't think that

97
00:06:48,817 --> 00:06:50,939
the combat or fight music needed to be different.

98
00:06:51,560 --> 00:06:53,141
And I thought we could do something.

99
00:06:53,522 --> 00:06:54,042
It could be fun.

100
00:06:55,701 --> 00:07:02,708
So along came a feature in the game called the phase indicator and it was in the right hand side of the screen and

101
00:07:02,728 --> 00:07:10,077
it told the player what was happening and it was first it would say zombie turn then plant turn

102
00:07:10,918 --> 00:07:11,518
zombie tricks

103
00:07:12,132 --> 00:07:15,435
combat phase, post-game, and then back to the next hand.

104
00:07:16,055 --> 00:07:18,438
So this was awesome, it communicated to the player

105
00:07:18,478 --> 00:07:20,620
what was happening, and also it gave us hooks

106
00:07:20,980 --> 00:07:23,383
for the music to hang our switches,

107
00:07:23,923 --> 00:07:26,526
basically switching from one kind of music to the next.

108
00:07:27,246 --> 00:07:30,509
And we decided to use that as the music structural driver

109
00:07:31,110 --> 00:07:32,191
for the game.

110
00:07:32,311 --> 00:07:32,371
So.

111
00:07:37,772 --> 00:07:42,016
With that, what are some music considerations when you have some kind of structural driver

112
00:07:42,697 --> 00:07:43,457
in the game like that?

113
00:07:44,018 --> 00:07:49,162
Well, first of all, the melodies per hero are indeterminate lengths, can be interrupted

114
00:07:49,222 --> 00:07:51,104
at any time based on the different gameplay.

115
00:07:51,784 --> 00:07:52,665
So that's going to be tricky.

116
00:07:53,486 --> 00:07:58,130
And I knew at that point that transitions would really, really be coming into play.

117
00:07:58,550 --> 00:08:01,353
And I didn't know what to do with them or how they would work or anything, but I knew

118
00:08:01,393 --> 00:08:02,013
that was going to be hard.

119
00:08:02,828 --> 00:08:07,852
And then I thought about, well, if we're going to go from one hero to another hero in a hand,

120
00:08:08,933 --> 00:08:11,695
what could make that hold together?

121
00:08:12,096 --> 00:08:15,078
And I thought, well, let's have common key centers per hand.

122
00:08:15,598 --> 00:08:20,862
So say you're in hand one, whether you're a plant or a zombie, you're in the key of

123
00:08:20,902 --> 00:08:21,343
G minor.

124
00:08:21,863 --> 00:08:27,588
Jump to hand four, both of them are in the hand of C minor, so common key centers per

125
00:08:27,608 --> 00:08:27,728
hand.

126
00:08:28,673 --> 00:08:34,116
Also, I decided at that time that I would set a common tempo of 125 BPM for the whole game.

127
00:08:34,216 --> 00:08:39,578
And I just set it and kept it there, and it kept everything tight and feeling together,

128
00:08:39,998 --> 00:08:41,439
and I'm glad I did that.

129
00:08:42,540 --> 00:08:48,842
So, these are choices and things that I was thinking about what to change, what not to change.

130
00:08:49,703 --> 00:08:53,004
Also in the hands, I thought about the drums and the progression of the drums.

131
00:08:53,544 --> 00:08:57,326
So in the early hands, you have light hand percussion, kind of mysterious hands,

132
00:08:57,646 --> 00:08:58,346
and then as you go...

133
00:08:58,806 --> 00:09:00,527
to the later hands you get the drum kit.

134
00:09:00,887 --> 00:09:02,228
So whether you're plant or zombie,

135
00:09:02,568 --> 00:09:04,509
you have the same kind of percussion.

136
00:09:04,669 --> 00:09:06,770
So that carries the glue between them as well.

137
00:09:07,390 --> 00:09:09,131
Of course there needs to be differentiators

138
00:09:09,671 --> 00:09:13,993
and I will talk about those.

139
00:09:14,073 --> 00:09:14,213
So.

140
00:09:15,509 --> 00:09:19,332
There's the plant faction and the zombie faction,

141
00:09:19,652 --> 00:09:21,473
and they're much like teams, right?

142
00:09:21,553 --> 00:09:24,135
So I'm on the plant team or I'm on the zombie team.

143
00:09:25,296 --> 00:09:25,996
How should that sound?

144
00:09:27,257 --> 00:09:29,599
And we're dealing with instrument sets

145
00:09:29,659 --> 00:09:31,180
in terms of how should they sound,

146
00:09:31,240 --> 00:09:34,262
not colors of uniforms, but instruments.

147
00:09:37,028 --> 00:09:40,211
I decided that there would be a common set of instruments between the plants and the

148
00:09:40,251 --> 00:09:42,133
zombies and that was mallets.

149
00:09:42,333 --> 00:09:43,634
Mallets are used all over the place.

150
00:09:44,635 --> 00:09:48,759
The walking baseline, pits, of course, is used all over the place as well throughout

151
00:09:49,260 --> 00:09:50,321
all heroes.

152
00:09:50,341 --> 00:09:54,985
There are a couple strings that are used also and a couple of other instruments that are

153
00:09:55,045 --> 00:09:56,206
the shared common set.

154
00:09:57,127 --> 00:09:59,089
But then you go into the perfection set.

155
00:09:59,750 --> 00:10:03,333
And for the plants, I decided they should be woodwinds.

156
00:10:03,573 --> 00:10:06,956
So woodwinds are the identifier for the plant faction.

157
00:10:07,997 --> 00:10:10,799
And within that, let's say you are a hero

158
00:10:10,839 --> 00:10:12,000
and you've selected your hero.

159
00:10:13,101 --> 00:10:16,024
There also will be one or two unique instruments

160
00:10:16,424 --> 00:10:17,385
per that hero.

161
00:10:17,485 --> 00:10:20,648
So every time you hear that hero, you go, ah, that's my guy

162
00:10:20,688 --> 00:10:21,228
or that's my gal.

163
00:10:21,769 --> 00:10:23,650
Like Spadau, for example.

164
00:10:24,311 --> 00:10:26,533
He's a funny, weird hero.

165
00:10:26,953 --> 00:10:28,134
And he has bassoon.

166
00:10:28,664 --> 00:10:31,085
And so that, of course, reflects his personalities.

167
00:10:32,706 --> 00:10:35,307
I should say that those choices of instruments

168
00:10:35,347 --> 00:10:39,049
came along as the personalities of the heroes

169
00:10:39,089 --> 00:10:39,689
came into being.

170
00:10:40,330 --> 00:10:42,150
So, you know, Spadaw being really weird,

171
00:10:42,190 --> 00:10:43,311
Bassoon seemed unnatural.

172
00:10:44,051 --> 00:10:46,252
So as the art came into place,

173
00:10:46,773 --> 00:10:49,654
I would choose different instruments per hero.

174
00:10:53,356 --> 00:10:55,297
So zombies, how should they sound?

175
00:10:56,305 --> 00:10:58,105
We had the common instrument set, as I mentioned,

176
00:10:58,305 --> 00:11:00,526
and then we had the per-faction instrument set.

177
00:11:00,886 --> 00:11:04,266
And so for zombies, I chose trombones and lower brass,

178
00:11:04,286 --> 00:11:05,267
because they're a little heavier,

179
00:11:06,027 --> 00:11:07,587
and that seemed to fit very well

180
00:11:07,627 --> 00:11:08,867
with their art and their style.

181
00:11:09,627 --> 00:11:11,408
And then, of course, there's the unique

182
00:11:11,508 --> 00:11:12,668
instrument set per hero.

183
00:11:13,288 --> 00:11:16,029
So as those heroes came into play,

184
00:11:16,709 --> 00:11:19,689
for example, like Rustbolt, who is really angular and weird,

185
00:11:19,809 --> 00:11:21,010
he got the eight-bit keys,

186
00:11:21,790 --> 00:11:23,990
and Gargantuar, who's,

187
00:11:24,792 --> 00:11:29,633
but he has a little guy up there, he's got the tuba and the Harmon muted trumpets.

188
00:11:30,033 --> 00:11:33,555
So these kinds of instrument choices reflect their own quirk.

189
00:11:38,596 --> 00:11:42,438
So, you know, I'm going along and playing with these different instruments and

190
00:11:43,098 --> 00:11:47,240
exploring, and along comes a marketing trailer. And most of the time,

191
00:11:47,480 --> 00:11:51,501
marketing is over here, right, and development's over here, and they're

192
00:11:51,561 --> 00:11:52,161
quite disparate.

193
00:11:53,752 --> 00:11:55,153
And we're all kind of used to that.

194
00:11:56,213 --> 00:11:58,675
And that was still the case right at this moment,

195
00:11:58,815 --> 00:11:59,195
I should say.

196
00:11:59,975 --> 00:12:02,656
The creative franchise director and head of marketing

197
00:12:02,676 --> 00:12:05,958
came and said, hey, we've got this great marketing trailer

198
00:12:05,998 --> 00:12:09,800
to announce the game.

199
00:12:10,020 --> 00:12:11,441
And the franchise director's like,

200
00:12:11,481 --> 00:12:12,641
hey, can you make it like The Incredibles?

201
00:12:12,661 --> 00:12:14,342
I'm like, sure I can.

202
00:12:14,742 --> 00:12:14,942
Okay.

203
00:12:15,440 --> 00:12:17,301
So I go out and I buy the Incredibles

204
00:12:17,341 --> 00:12:19,062
and I go out and buy the Incredibles soundtracks

205
00:12:19,102 --> 00:12:20,803
and I think any composer in the room,

206
00:12:20,843 --> 00:12:22,805
if somebody says, hey, can you do it like this?

207
00:12:22,845 --> 00:12:24,086
You go out and you get that music

208
00:12:24,126 --> 00:12:26,087
and you study it and you breathe it and you live it.

209
00:12:26,507 --> 00:12:29,389
You try to become it so you can kind of understand the style

210
00:12:30,150 --> 00:12:32,431
and I did that and then spent a couple of weeks

211
00:12:32,491 --> 00:12:34,893
working with the franchise creative director

212
00:12:35,653 --> 00:12:38,355
on the trailer and we came to a really nice piece,

213
00:12:38,395 --> 00:12:41,177
a two and a half minute trailer with that style

214
00:12:42,138 --> 00:12:45,020
and we were going to do a live recording, which is awesome.

215
00:12:45,694 --> 00:12:53,059
So it's Monday and I had told Panther Modern that I would be handing him the music or the

216
00:12:53,099 --> 00:12:56,641
sessions the next day to prepare for our session at Bustier on Friday.

217
00:12:57,462 --> 00:13:02,506
But that Monday night, our head of marketing and franchise director played it for EA's

218
00:13:02,746 --> 00:13:03,667
VP of marketing.

219
00:13:05,088 --> 00:13:06,168
And he's like, oh, okay.

220
00:13:06,899 --> 00:13:10,061
That's great, but what if it's a little more Batman-y?

221
00:13:10,622 --> 00:13:13,824
You know, like 1960s, but kind of the 1980s remake.

222
00:13:15,185 --> 00:13:17,466
So they brought me in on Monday around 7 o'clock,

223
00:13:17,546 --> 00:13:20,088
and they said, well, what do you think of this?

224
00:13:20,769 --> 00:13:24,251
And I listened to it, and man, I had to agree.

225
00:13:24,831 --> 00:13:25,612
It was really awesome.

226
00:13:26,232 --> 00:13:26,793
It was so good.

227
00:13:28,297 --> 00:13:34,019
You know, I had to quickly let go of the two weeks of work that I had done and the idea

228
00:13:34,040 --> 00:13:35,360
of how it was going to go.

229
00:13:36,141 --> 00:13:39,462
And our head of marketing said, so what do you think?

230
00:13:40,583 --> 00:13:42,024
Hmm, yes, good.

231
00:13:43,124 --> 00:13:46,186
Can I have till tomorrow morning and I'll try to do that?

232
00:13:46,786 --> 00:13:47,606
And he said, oh, sure.

233
00:13:48,421 --> 00:13:51,622
And meanwhile, I'm like, oh my god, I've got Stan lined up.

234
00:13:51,642 --> 00:13:53,183
We're going to record on Friday.

235
00:13:53,663 --> 00:13:57,725
But I just worked that night and tried to write in that style

236
00:13:58,625 --> 00:14:00,406
and came up with something pretty good

237
00:14:00,466 --> 00:14:01,287
by the next morning.

238
00:14:01,887 --> 00:14:04,068
And they came in and like, oh yeah, that's great.

239
00:14:04,628 --> 00:14:06,069
So I wrote it all out.

240
00:14:06,929 --> 00:14:08,450
We still recorded on Friday.

241
00:14:08,710 --> 00:14:10,971
And then we brought in a drum kit and bass

242
00:14:11,291 --> 00:14:14,292
and made this kind of 60s spy genre type thing.

243
00:14:16,029 --> 00:14:20,233
It worked out really well, and I'm really grateful for this marketing trailer

244
00:14:20,893 --> 00:14:25,137
because it was this watershed moment for part of the style of the music of the game.

245
00:14:25,718 --> 00:14:28,420
And also a big trust was established with the team.

246
00:14:29,061 --> 00:14:32,645
