00:29:28,403 --> 00:29:28,843
well together.

506
00:29:34,794 --> 00:29:36,975
So, along comes the MIDI phase.

507
00:29:38,676 --> 00:29:39,717
I like this part of the story.

508
00:29:40,757 --> 00:29:44,379
So, Guy Whitmore had decided, you know,

509
00:29:44,399 --> 00:29:46,580
this is a great pop cap enterprise project

510
00:29:46,600 --> 00:29:50,262
that we should record our own sample library

511
00:29:50,342 --> 00:29:51,623
for our games, for mobile games.

512
00:29:53,870 --> 00:29:58,294
He and I worked together to decide which instruments we should record based on the projects that

513
00:29:58,314 --> 00:30:02,617
were in production at the time and also looking out to the future what would be good ones

514
00:30:02,657 --> 00:30:03,358
to have in general.

515
00:30:03,898 --> 00:30:05,199
So we came up with a list of 24 instruments.

516
00:30:07,158 --> 00:30:08,438
I always knew this was in the plan.

517
00:30:08,458 --> 00:30:12,839
It didn't happen, it happened midway through production for Heroes.

518
00:30:13,299 --> 00:30:17,960
I'd already finished seven Heroes by this time writing for East-West libraries.

519
00:30:19,280 --> 00:30:24,081
But we were undergoing this sample library exercise and knowing that we'd be moving over

520
00:30:24,121 --> 00:30:25,522
to those samples eventually.

521
00:30:26,442 --> 00:30:28,022
And you may ask why?

522
00:30:28,822 --> 00:30:31,903
But mobile, you know, we're always thinking about size and ways to be smart.

523
00:30:32,534 --> 00:30:34,215
and this is a really smart way to do it.

524
00:30:34,675 --> 00:30:37,876
And also no licensing fees by having a sample library

525
00:30:37,896 --> 00:30:39,097
that you pull from within the game.

526
00:30:39,577 --> 00:30:42,878
So, we went to Studio X

527
00:30:43,038 --> 00:30:44,779
and we recorded these 24 instruments.

528
00:30:45,639 --> 00:30:47,540
Three different articulations,

529
00:30:47,700 --> 00:30:49,361
three different dynamics per instrument.

530
00:30:49,981 --> 00:30:51,101
And then Guy,

531
00:30:52,480 --> 00:30:56,483
hired Panther Modern and his team of specialists,

532
00:30:56,523 --> 00:30:58,063
which maybe there's some in the room today.

533
00:30:58,524 --> 00:30:59,704
There are many people who helped us

534
00:31:00,145 --> 00:31:02,426
in terms of editing all of these materials

535
00:31:02,546 --> 00:31:04,547
and creating these mirrored sets,

536
00:31:04,887 --> 00:31:07,208
a mirrored set for contact and for WISE.

537
00:31:07,248 --> 00:31:10,650
So you write in your DAW with your contact set

538
00:31:10,730 --> 00:31:11,931
and then you bring it over to WISE

539
00:31:12,451 --> 00:31:15,273
and it's pretty darn close set.

540
00:31:15,433 --> 00:31:18,174
So it worked beautifully and they did a great job.

541
00:31:18,214 --> 00:31:19,955
So thank you, thank you so much.

542
00:31:23,220 --> 00:31:28,083
So some of our instruments here, alto flute, saxophone,

543
00:31:29,824 --> 00:31:32,786
this is just our list of instruments that I used mostly.

544
00:31:34,487 --> 00:31:39,530
Then I brought them over to Logic and I'll talk about that.

545
00:31:41,451 --> 00:31:44,073
Hired Panther Modern to help with the MIDI arrangements

546
00:31:44,173 --> 00:31:45,133
because I was going to take.

547
00:31:45,937 --> 00:31:50,040
the seven sets I already had and moved them over to the PopCap sample library.

548
00:31:50,540 --> 00:31:52,362
So I asked him if he could help with that.

549
00:31:53,202 --> 00:31:56,004
And also asked him about MIDI exporting,

550
00:31:56,364 --> 00:31:59,026
because Pro Tools didn't seem very good at MIDI exporting.

551
00:31:59,566 --> 00:32:01,408
So he said, yeah, Logic is way better.

552
00:32:02,048 --> 00:32:05,590
So I decided, well, OK, then I will learn Logic.

553
00:32:06,211 --> 00:32:10,314
And I think at PopCap, no one's too shy to learn a new DAW

554
00:32:10,754 --> 00:32:12,095
in the middle of everything.

555
00:32:12,603 --> 00:32:15,845
And I thank you all for being so brave.

556
00:32:17,106 --> 00:32:18,487
Because I'm like, OK, I can do this too.

557
00:32:19,247 --> 00:32:21,149
So I decided I'll learn logic.

558
00:32:21,429 --> 00:32:24,751
And what was great about that is some of you probably all

559
00:32:24,771 --> 00:32:28,414
know this, but there's such a great community around logic.

560
00:32:28,434 --> 00:32:30,255
You go onto YouTube, you ask any question,

561
00:32:30,315 --> 00:32:31,816
and there is a tutorial video.

562
00:32:32,777 --> 00:32:35,959
And I basically got up and running very quickly,

563
00:32:36,059 --> 00:32:38,501
one or two weeks, and I felt like I was fluid.

564
00:32:38,541 --> 00:32:40,342
And if I had any questions, I'd just go to YouTube.

565
00:32:40,362 --> 00:32:40,582
Hello.

566
00:32:42,255 --> 00:32:44,396
all you gracious people who've shared information,

567
00:32:45,477 --> 00:32:45,997
really helped me.

568
00:32:46,578 --> 00:32:47,978
So I was able to get up and running quickly.

569
00:32:48,899 --> 00:32:51,180
And I want to say, I am not a Pro Tools hater.

570
00:32:52,641 --> 00:32:54,261
I still do like it for multiple movies,

571
00:32:54,401 --> 00:32:55,482
I think it's a great tool,

572
00:32:55,822 --> 00:32:58,664
but I do think it's good to choose the right tool

573
00:32:58,944 --> 00:32:59,424
for the job.

574
00:33:00,044 --> 00:33:01,685
And Logic was the best for MIDI,

575
00:33:02,245 --> 00:33:03,906
and I still also use Pro Tools.

576
00:33:06,287 --> 00:33:08,148
So, I had given

577
00:33:08,605 --> 00:33:14,729
Green Shadow was the first one to Stan Lippard to do the MIDI arrangements and to the PopCap

578
00:33:14,749 --> 00:33:15,089
samples.

579
00:33:16,150 --> 00:33:19,792
He came into PopCap and we sat down and we listened to it.

580
00:33:22,645 --> 00:33:25,425
And it did not sound the same.

581
00:33:25,445 --> 00:33:27,846
I'd been writing to the East-West libraries, primarily,

582
00:33:28,666 --> 00:33:30,947
that are beautiful, and different.

583
00:33:31,827 --> 00:33:34,707
And our PopCap sample library is fantastic, too,

584
00:33:34,747 --> 00:33:35,788
but it's totally different.

585
00:33:36,248 --> 00:33:37,708
So the sounds were not the same.

586
00:33:38,388 --> 00:33:40,789
And the music, even though they were the same cues,

587
00:33:40,829 --> 00:33:42,669
it just felt wrong.

588
00:33:42,729 --> 00:33:44,150
And I had a day of depression.

589
00:33:44,470 --> 00:33:45,370
But I pulled right out.

590
00:33:46,190 --> 00:33:48,951
And I learned at that moment that a French horn

591
00:33:48,991 --> 00:33:51,171
from one sample library is not the same as a French horn,

592
00:33:51,211 --> 00:33:52,352
necessarily, to the other.

593
00:33:53,126 --> 00:33:59,072
or the mallets, or several instruments in this case, weren't matches.

594
00:33:59,532 --> 00:34:05,838
And so I think it's very important, if you can, to write to the sample library that you'll

595
00:34:05,858 --> 00:34:07,640
be using ultimately at the end.

596
00:34:08,320 --> 00:34:09,582
Try to start there if you can.

597
00:34:11,524 --> 00:34:16,328
It took a lot of time and effort to get to a place where I was comfortable with this

598
00:34:16,809 --> 00:34:17,529
sample library.

599
00:34:18,479 --> 00:34:22,302
A couple of weeks with green shadow and then I was fully comfortable with it.

600
00:34:22,842 --> 00:34:24,163
But we had to learn techniques.

601
00:34:25,304 --> 00:34:25,664
So we did.

602
00:34:25,724 --> 00:34:29,788
We sat down for a couple of weeks and we learned that layering helped, layering different kinds

603
00:34:29,828 --> 00:34:35,072
of instruments, switching out, reorchestration in some cases, velocity changes.

604
00:34:36,120 --> 00:34:39,682
Actually, duration changes in the mallets were really key.

605
00:34:40,443 --> 00:34:42,624
It took, as I said, about two weeks on that.

606
00:34:42,945 --> 00:34:45,727
And then after we learned some of these tricks,

607
00:34:46,987 --> 00:34:49,429
it went faster per each hero after that.

608
00:34:50,950 --> 00:34:52,651
And this is some of the layering that was done.

609
00:34:53,652 --> 00:34:56,033
Didn't lean as, I leaned a lot on the French horns

610
00:34:56,874 --> 00:34:58,955
in East-West, and then for PopCap,

611
00:34:59,055 --> 00:35:00,837
I leaned more on the trombones.

612
00:35:01,817 --> 00:35:05,140
And then did more layering with vibes.

613
00:35:07,455 --> 00:35:10,162
This is how it sounds for Superbrains MIDI.

614
00:35:38,789 --> 00:35:38,929
Aaah...

615
00:36:11,114 --> 00:36:16,439
All right, so I think it turned out really well and eventually after getting

616
00:36:16,479 --> 00:36:22,465
them all into MIDI and into the game, I totally forgot what it sounded like

617
00:36:22,485 --> 00:36:27,850
before. I love it and I actually think it fits way better with the aesthetic and I

618
00:36:27,910 --> 00:36:33,095
love it. I just grew to totally love MIDI and I'll tell you more why later.

619
00:36:35,293 --> 00:36:38,353
So, I wanna talk a little bit about size.

620
00:36:39,114 --> 00:36:42,754
We are a mobile studio, and we have to be very mindful

621
00:36:42,774 --> 00:36:45,735
of our size because of the devices that we are played on.

622
00:36:46,635 --> 00:36:49,496
And about midway through, we went through an exercise

623
00:36:49,596 --> 00:36:51,416
and established what our size would be.

624
00:36:52,016 --> 00:36:53,677
And we sort of claimed 80 megs.

625
00:36:54,717 --> 00:36:57,297
40 for music, 40 for sound effects and VO.

626
00:36:58,078 --> 00:36:59,718
Luca made a beautiful pie chart.

627
00:37:00,078 --> 00:37:03,059
We met with the TD, we showed it to the executive producer,

628
00:37:03,439 --> 00:37:04,759
and they said, fine, okay.

629
00:37:05,833 --> 00:37:08,814
Now, at that time, we were still kind of in this Hearthstone

630
00:37:08,934 --> 00:37:11,715
era, that's sort of a big game.

631
00:37:14,075 --> 00:37:16,776
But now, at this point, we're in late production.

632
00:37:16,796 --> 00:37:18,076
I wanna switch to late production.

633
00:37:19,036 --> 00:37:22,257
And along came Clash Royale, and that was a quick game.

634
00:37:23,377 --> 00:37:25,798
It loaded quickly, and everybody was loving it,

635
00:37:25,818 --> 00:37:30,759
and we had some pressure to come down to 30 megabytes.

636
00:37:31,219 --> 00:37:32,880
Right, we got an email over the weekend,

637
00:37:32,980 --> 00:37:34,780
and we're like, oh, you're too big,

638
00:37:34,820 --> 00:37:35,720
you need to be 30 megabytes.

639
00:37:37,821 --> 00:37:41,342
I think we all broke out in rashes at that moment.

640
00:37:42,962 --> 00:37:49,124
The executive producer came by our meeting fortunately that day and he said, hey, just

641
00:37:49,284 --> 00:37:49,784
see what you can do.

642
00:37:50,404 --> 00:37:51,705
So we saw what we could do.

643
00:37:52,225 --> 00:37:54,185
And we held to 60 megabytes.

644
00:37:55,046 --> 00:37:57,826
And with our wise wizard, Damien Kastbauer right here.

645
00:37:58,622 --> 00:38:02,985
He pulled all the levers and whys to make it work

646
00:38:03,425 --> 00:38:05,266
and to go down to 60 and make it sound awesome.

647
00:38:05,866 --> 00:38:08,448
He used over 21 different compression settings

648
00:38:08,989 --> 00:38:10,149
for the different sound types,

649
00:38:11,070 --> 00:38:12,711
really massaging it and crafting it.

650
00:38:13,552 --> 00:38:16,033
We switched some things from stereo to mono,

651
00:38:16,053 --> 00:38:16,774
but not everything.

652
00:38:17,694 --> 00:38:19,596
We streamed all the wave music

653
00:38:20,676 --> 00:38:24,279
and we streamed larger wave assets, like hero assets.

654
00:38:25,163 --> 00:38:29,126
We also reduced the instrument ranges for the instrument sets.

655
00:38:29,747 --> 00:38:32,850
So in some cases, if there's a higher range that's not needed,

656
00:38:33,370 --> 00:38:36,132
I could just stretch out the note or just remove that.

657
00:38:36,373 --> 00:38:38,414
So I just went in and kind of did some pruning.

658
00:38:39,315 --> 00:38:40,416
And that worked out well.

659
00:38:40,876 --> 00:38:43,619
Also reduced the variation on the stingers of the block sounds.

660
00:38:43,739 --> 00:38:45,240
Bow, bow, end of game.

661
00:38:47,122 --> 00:38:48,983
And we got down to 60, and it sounds great.

662
00:38:50,044 --> 00:38:50,805
And that's where we stayed.

663
00:38:53,887 --> 00:38:55,209
Now, music, the late phase.

664
00:38:56,350 --> 00:38:58,693
We'd been playing the game now for quite some time.

665
00:38:58,774 --> 00:39:00,075
The music has been in the game,

666
00:39:00,676 --> 00:39:02,919
and it hasn't changed too much for several months.

667
00:39:03,780 --> 00:39:04,341
How's it working?

668
00:39:05,162 --> 00:39:05,862
How's it not working?

669
00:39:07,474 --> 00:39:09,396
Luke had been playing it a lot and he was like,

670
00:39:09,436 --> 00:39:12,038
well, he was saying that in hand eight,

671
00:39:12,058 --> 00:39:13,980
because his games were longer than five minutes.

672
00:39:14,060 --> 00:39:17,903
So some real world stuff, real world info is coming in now.

673
00:39:17,923 --> 00:39:20,545
You know, these are, sometimes they're shorter

674
00:39:20,585 --> 00:39:22,167
than five minutes, but sometimes, you know,

675
00:39:22,187 --> 00:39:22,987
it's an eight minute game.

676
00:39:23,588 --> 00:39:24,529
And how's that working?

677
00:39:25,189 --> 00:39:30,554
It wasn't responding quite as much as we wanted it to,

678
00:39:30,634 --> 00:39:31,415
as I wanted it to.

679
00:39:31,935 --> 00:39:34,557
You remember, I wanted it to really be the

680
00:39:34,988 --> 00:39:38,031
connected to the gameplay experience and responsive

681
00:39:38,311 --> 00:39:40,813
and for it to give emotional feedback to the player.

682
00:39:42,074 --> 00:39:44,516
So, how could we make it more responsive?

683
00:39:45,557 --> 00:39:48,099
MIDI was going to become our friend.

684
00:39:51,081 --> 00:39:52,242
Now, one thing I thought was,

685
00:39:52,302 --> 00:39:56,365
ha, well, when you get further in the game

686
00:39:56,446 --> 00:39:58,047
and you're up by a certain amount,

687
00:39:58,347 --> 00:40:00,649
you wanna feel good, you wanna feel lifted.

688
00:40:01,530 --> 00:40:04,052
You know, remember Barry Manilow.

689
00:40:04,475 --> 00:40:05,096
How he did that?

690
00:40:05,656 --> 00:40:06,456
He transposed.

691
00:40:06,896 --> 00:40:07,556
Okay, and it worked.

692
00:40:08,036 --> 00:40:09,977
So, not all of you remember Barry Manilow,

693
00:40:09,997 --> 00:40:10,697
and I realize that.

694
00:40:11,677 --> 00:40:12,918
Anyway, he did transposition.

695
00:40:12,938 --> 00:40:15,378
I'm like, oh yeah, we should try that.

696
00:40:16,319 --> 00:40:20,160
So, Damien and I sat down together and figured out,

697
00:40:20,940 --> 00:40:21,860
Damien was like, oh.

698
00:40:23,035 --> 00:40:25,775
we could, huh, could we do this with MIDI?

699
00:40:26,416 --> 00:40:29,316
And so we created an RTPC

700
00:40:30,177 --> 00:40:32,617
for players' relative health in Wwise.

701
00:40:33,298 --> 00:40:35,538
And with MIDI, what we were able to do

702
00:40:35,998 --> 00:40:37,519
was if you're up by five points,

703
00:40:38,399 --> 00:40:40,140
all the MIDI music went up a whole step.

704
00:40:40,920 --> 00:40:42,260
And if you're up by 10 points,

705
00:40:42,460 --> 00:40:44,821
all the MIDI music went up two whole steps.

706
00:40:46,285 --> 00:40:46,786
And it worked.

707
00:40:47,266 --> 00:40:47,827
It was awesome.

708
00:40:48,007 --> 00:40:49,969
That's why we love MIDI.

709
00:40:50,370 --> 00:40:51,251
It really was flexible.

710
00:40:51,551 --> 00:40:53,513
It was something that you can really work with.

711
00:40:54,874 --> 00:40:56,656
And at that point, the waves were

712
00:40:56,696 --> 00:40:57,757
starting to become an issue.

713
00:40:57,777 --> 00:40:59,920
Because remember, this is a hybrid score.

714
00:41:00,580 --> 00:41:03,083
And the super block waves, ba-pow,

715
00:41:03,303 --> 00:41:04,925
would actually happen over the sections

716
00:41:04,965 --> 00:41:05,886
where there's MIDI music.

717
00:41:06,838 --> 00:41:10,860
And if you transpose your MIDI and you don't transpose those brass stingers, it does not

718
00:41:10,900 --> 00:41:11,320
sound good.

719
00:41:12,180 --> 00:41:17,703
So they were feeling kind of like clunky, the waves, like pulling us down.

720
00:41:18,563 --> 00:41:24,766
And we utilized the same RTPC, but used playback speed for the waves.

721
00:41:24,826 --> 00:41:29,608
And we're able to get that working, but it was really not as easy to do.

722
00:41:29,668 --> 00:41:32,269
But it did get sounding great.

723
00:41:34,697 --> 00:41:37,017
Then we utilized the same health parameter,

724
00:41:37,117 --> 00:41:41,098
same point spread, and added an overlay track

725
00:41:41,258 --> 00:41:43,739
to the plants when they're not doing well,

726
00:41:44,059 --> 00:41:45,420
and the zombies when they're not doing well.

727
00:41:45,940 --> 00:41:47,720
For the plants I used a bass clarinet pattern,

728
00:41:47,840 --> 00:41:49,441
and the zombies I used a trombone pattern,

729
00:41:50,001 --> 00:41:53,382
and so the same RTPC would call that for a negative

730
00:41:53,402 --> 00:41:54,422
when you're down by 10.

731
00:41:57,483 --> 00:41:59,364
A different health parameter that we used

732
00:42:00,364 --> 00:42:01,805
when the player was not doing well

733
00:42:02,205 --> 00:42:04,385
was we utilized parameters to drive switches.

734
00:42:06,885 --> 00:42:10,246
And by that, I added a horizontal music layer,

735
00:42:10,426 --> 00:42:14,407
an overlay track, and it switched to a low health sub-track

736
00:42:14,988 --> 00:42:17,088
to a cello, ostinato, and bass pitts part.

737
00:42:17,908 --> 00:42:21,049
So whether you are a zombie or a plant, it's the same.

738
00:42:21,169 --> 00:42:23,690
You're down to your last five and you're not doing well.

739
00:42:23,810 --> 00:42:27,891
Yeah, you kind of got that JAWS type thing happening.

740
00:42:29,912 --> 00:42:32,272
We also, at this phase, because we're kind of like,

741
00:42:32,312 --> 00:42:33,393
how can we get this more responsive?

742
00:42:35,557 --> 00:42:41,344
Luca had been thinking about those kinds of ideas way early on, and he had this EKG, we

743
00:42:41,364 --> 00:42:46,771
called it, game parameter, which was a combination of many different things of how the player

744
00:42:46,811 --> 00:42:47,372
was feeling.

745
00:42:47,432 --> 00:42:51,396
So a combination of many different things I cannot explain right now.

746
00:42:53,003 --> 00:42:54,444
But basically, if you follow that parameter,

747
00:42:54,464 --> 00:42:56,444
it would be an intensity change.

748
00:42:56,945 --> 00:43:00,826
And so we thought, oh, we'll try that with Spadau and Cyborg

749
00:43:01,487 --> 00:43:02,687
on some drums.

750
00:43:02,747 --> 00:43:03,788
Let's try it on some drums.

751
00:43:04,088 --> 00:43:06,389
So we added some subtracts and layers with drums.

752
00:43:06,889 --> 00:43:09,210
And it was working in the game, and we could hear it.

753
00:43:09,770 --> 00:43:11,631
But the material itself, the drum tracks,

754
